38","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1070–1129":"1070–1129","1075–1143":"1075–1143","1099":"1099","22 August 1138":"22 August 1138","1143":"1143","1075":"1075","1097":"1097","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Great Harwood, Lancashire, England","Pontefract, Yorkshire, England":"Pontefract, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lassy in Calvados, named from a Gaulish personal name <i>Lascius</i> (of uncertain origin and meaning) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lasee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Irish   Lacy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":7,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Lacy was born in 1099, in Pontefract, Yorkshire, England, his father, Robert de Lacy Baron of Pontefract, was 29 and his mother, Mathilde de Perche, was 24. He had at least 1 daughter. He died on 22 August 1138, in Great Harwood, Lancashire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1099–22 August 1138":"1099–22. august 1138","1095–1166":"1095–1166","1096–1141":"1096–1141","1097–1166":"1097–1166","1097–1177":"1097–1177","1099–1138":"1099–1138","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1070–1129":"1070–1129","1075–1143":"1075–1143","1099":"1099","22 August 1138":"22. august 1138","1143":"1143","1075":"1075","1097":"1097","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Great Harwood, Lancashire, England","Pontefract, Yorkshire, England":"Pontefract, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1099–22 August 1138":"1099–22. elokuuta 1138","1095–1166":"1095–1166","1096–1141":"109